{"title_page": "W. D. Cocker", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''W. D. Cocker''' (1882 in [[Rutherglen]] &ndash; 1970) was a Scottish poet who wrote in both [[Scots language|Scots]] and English.\n\n==Life==\nW. D. Cocker was born into a family of Glasgow merchants.<ref name=Edinburgh>Maurice Lindsay and Lesley Duncan, ''The Edinburgh book of twentieth-century Scottish poetry'', p.378</ref>\n\nIn the [[First World War]], he served with the [[Highland Light Infantry]], and was taken prisoner in 1917. His war poetry is fairly limited in scope, but includes the poems \"Up the Line to Poelkapelle\", \"[[The Sniper (poem)|The Sniper]]\" and a five-part sonnet cycle entitled \"Sonnets in Captivity\".\n\nAfter the war Cocker entered the account department of the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'', and was the paper's drama citic until retirement in 1956.<ref name=Edinburgh/> He is best known for his humorous poems in Scots, often on Biblical themes, such as \"The Deluge\", on the story of Noah and the Flood. Books of his poems include \"Poems: Scots and English\", \"Further Poems\", \"New Poems\" and \"Randon Rhymes and Ballads\".<ref>all published by Brown, Son & Ferguson, Ltd., Glasgow</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cocker, W. D.}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:People from Rutherglen]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n'''W. D. Cocker''' (1882 in [[Rutherglen]] &ndash; 1970) was a Scottish poet who wrote in both [[Scots language|Scots]] and English.\n\n==Life==\nW. D. Cocker was born into a family of Glasgow merchants.<ref name=Edinburgh>Maurice Lindsay and Lesley Duncan, ''The Edinburgh book of twentieth-century Scottish poetry'', p.378</ref>\n\nIn the [[First World War]], he served with the [[Highland Light Infantry]], and was taken prisoner in 1917. His war poetry is fairly limited in scope, but includes the poems \"Up the Line to Poelkapelle\", \"[[The Sniper (poem)|The Sniper]]\" and a five-part sonnet cycle entitled \"Sonnets in Captivity\".\n\nAfter the war Cocker entered the account department of the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'', and was the paper's drama citic until retirement in 1956.<ref name=Edinburgh/> He is best known for his humorous poems in Scots, often on Biblical themes, such as \"The Deluge\", on the story of Noah and the Flood. Books of his poems include \"Poems: Scots and English\", \"Further Poems\", \"New Poems\" and \"Randon Rhymes and Ballads\".<ref>all published by Brown, Son & Ferguson, Ltd., Glasgow</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cocker, W. D.}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:People from Rutherglen]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._D._Cocker"}
{"title_page": "San Clemente-class oil tanker", "text_new": "{{short description|Class of oil tankers}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= [[File:USNS Mercy leaving San Diego Bay.jpg|300px|USNS Mercy]]\n|Ship image size=300px\n|Ship caption= USNS ''Mercy'' leaving San Diego Bay, May 2008\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Builders=[[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]]\n|Operators=\n|Class before=\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=T-AH-19\n|Built range=1974-1978\n|In service range=\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=\n|Total ships completed=13\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active=\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships scrapped=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Oil tanker]] - two [[Hospital ship]]s\n|Ship tonnage=89,700 [[Deadweight tonnage|dwt]]\n|Ship length={{convert|894|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|105|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|64|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship propulsion=Steam, {{convert|24,500|BHP|abbr=on}} \n|Ship speed={{convert|16.5|kn|lk=in}} at 90% MCR, Full Load \n|Ship capacity=32,5000 Cu feet\n|Ship crew= 21  (Hospital ship 1,000)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Defense.gov News Photo 071015-N-6278K-167.jpg|right|thumb|USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)]]\n\nThe '''''San Clemente''-class oil tanker''' is a class of [[Oil tanker]]s built by [[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]] (NASSCO), [[San Diego]]. The size places them in the category of super [[Tanker (ship)|tankers]]. They were built to serve the [[Trans-Alaska Pipeline System]]. At the time of completion National Steel and Shipbuilding Company was equally owned by Kaiser Industries Corporation and Morrison-Knudsen Company, Inc.\n\nNASSCO also built the San Diego-class tankers at 180,000-dwt, Catalina-class tankers at 150,000- dwt and the Coronado-class tankers at 38,300-dwt. NASSCO also built for the US Navy [[Yellowstone-class destroyer tender]] (AD-41 class) at 19,800-ton each.<ref>[http://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/197801/content/delivers-clementeclass-subsidiary-209658 Marine link, NASSCO Delivers Third In Series Of Four San Clemente-Class Tankers For OSG Subsidiary]</ref><ref>[https://nassco.com/products/construction/commercial-construction/commercial-ship-portfolio/ National Steel and Shipbuilding Company, Commercial Ship Portfolio]</ref>\n\nTwo ships were converted by NASSCO to T-AH-19 [[hospital ship]]s. The two hospital ships were delivered to the [[US Navy]] in 1986 and 1987 as [[Auxiliary ship|Naval Auxiliary Fleet ships]]. The two provided for the Navy deployable acute medical care facility. Each has 1,000-bed medical care unit. They are used for Armed forces and mercy mission to damaged locations, like after a [[Typhoon]].<ref>[http://www.nauticexpo.com/prod/general-dynamics-nassco/product-32138-195925.html Nuatic Exop, Oil tanker cargo ship, SAN CLEMENTE CLASS]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |title=Patient Care |website=Command Facilities |publisher=USNS Mercy |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323010700/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/Commandinfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |archivedate=23 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"med.navy.mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |title=Command Mission |website=USNS Mercy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813132035/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |archivedate=2009-08-13|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"med.navy.mil\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/logi-en/1997/lo-1610.htm |title=NATO Logistics Handbook: Chapter 16: Medical Support |work=nato.int |date=October 1997 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnscomfort/Pages/default.aspx|title=Home|work=navy.mil|accessdate=4 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426120150/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnscomfort/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate=26 April 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2012/02/16/usns-comforts-move-from-baltimore-to-norfolk-to-save-navy-time-money|title=USNS Comfort\u2019s Move From Baltimore To Norfolk To Save Navy Time & Money \u00ab CBS Baltimore|work=cbslocal.com|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\nEach ship is 894 feet long, with a beam of 105 feet and depths-draft of 64 feet. This is the maximum size, known as [[Panamax]], that can pass through the [[Panama Canal]]. All the ships in the class have a [[double hull]] bottom for safety. They came with anti-collision [[radar]], [[bacteria]]-[[enzyme]] [[sewage treatment]] plant and high-capacity clean [[ballast]] systems.\n<ref>Tanker Construction Program: Environmental Impact Statement, Volume 1, page 2-31</ref>\n<ref>[http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/large/nassco.htm shipbuildinghistory.com, NASSCO, San Diego CA]</ref>\n\n==Owners==\n*Aeron Marine Shipping Co.\n*Third Group, Inc.\n*Maritime Overseas Corp. (now [[Overseas Shipholding Group]])\n*Chestnut Shipping Co.\n\n== Ships in class ==\n*SS ''Beaver State'', renamed ''Liberty Belle'' in 1988, scrapped 1995\n*SS ''American Heritage'', Scrapped 1994\n*SS ''Golden Dolphin'', launched on January 19, 1974, Explosion/sunk off Azores, 1982\n*SS ''Golden Endeavor'', launched 1976,  Scrapped 1995\n*SS ''Aframax''\n*SS ''Overseas New York'', Scrapped 2004\n*SS ''Overseas Chicago'', Scrapped 2004 \n*SS ''Overseas Ohio'', renamed S/R ''Hinchinbrook'' in  2000, scrapped 2004 \n*SS ''Overseas Washington'',  Scrapped 2006\n*SS ''Overseas Arctic''  <ref>[https://openjurist.org/27/f3d/1104/sun-company-inc-v-ss-overseas-arctic-bp-usa Open Jury SS Overseas Arctic]</ref>\n*SS ''Chestnut Hill'', launched June 22, 1976. \n*SS ''Kittaning'', launched February 20, 1977.\n\n===Converted to hospital ships===\n*[[USNS Mercy (T-AH-19)|USNS ''Mercy'' (T-AH-19)]] built as ''SS Worth'' in 1974, converted in 1984.\n*[[USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)|USNS ''Comfort'' (T-AH-20)]] Built as SS ''Rose City'', laid down on May 1975 converted in 1986.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|USNS Mercy (T-AH-19)}}\n{{Commons category|USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)}}\n*{{NVR url|id=AH19|title=Naval Vessel Register entry for ''Mercy''}}\n\n{{Mercy class hospital ship}}\n{{ModernMerchantShipTypes}}\n{{Ship measurements}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Clemente-class oil tanker}}\n[[Category:Ships built in San Diego]]\n[[Category:1975 ships]]\n[[Category:Oil tankers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Class of oil tankers}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= [[File:USNS Mercy leaving San Diego Bay.jpg|300px|USNS Mercy]]\n|Ship image size=300px\n|Ship caption= USNS ''Mercy'' leaving San Diego Bay, May 2008\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Builders=[[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]]\n|Operators=\n|Class before=\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=T-AH-19\n|Built range=1974-1978\n|In service range=\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=\n|Total ships completed=13\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active=\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships scrapped=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Oil tanker]] - two [[Hospital ship]]s\n|Ship tonnage=89,700 [[Deadweight tonnage|dwt]]\n|Ship length={{convert|894|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|105|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|64|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship propulsion=Steam, {{convert|24,500|BHP|abbr=on}} \n|Ship speed={{convert|16.5|kn|lk=in}} at 90% MCR, Full Load \n|Ship capacity=32,5000 Cu feet\n|Ship crew= 21  (Hospital ship 1,000)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Defense.gov News Photo 071015-N-6278K-167.jpg|right|thumb|USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)]]\n\nThe '''''San Clemente''-class oil tanker''' is a class of [[Oil tanker]]s built by [[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]] (NASSCO), [[San Diego]]. The size places them in the category of super [[Tanker (ship)|tankers]]. They were built to serve the [[Trans-Alaska Pipeline System]]. At the time of completion National Steel and Shipbuilding Company was equally owned by Kaiser Industries Corporation and Morrison-Knudsen Company, Inc.\n\nNASSCO also built the San Diego-class tankers at 180,000-dwt, Catalina-class tankers at 150,000- dwt and the Coronado-class tankers at 38,300-dwt. NASSCO also built for the US Navy [[Yellowstone-class destroyer tender]] (AD-41 class) at 19,800-ton each.<ref>[http://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/197801/content/delivers-clementeclass-subsidiary-209658 Marine link, NASSCO Delivers Third In Series Of Four San Clemente-Class Tankers For OSG Subsidiary]</ref><ref>[https://nassco.com/products/construction/commercial-construction/commercial-ship-portfolio/ National Steel and Shipbuilding Company, Commercial Ship Portfolio]</ref>\n\nTwo ships were converted by NASSCO to T-AH-19 [[hospital ship]]s. The two hospital ships were delivered to the [[US Navy]] in 1986 and 1987 as [[Auxiliary ship|Naval Auxiliary Fleet ships]]. The two provided for the Navy deployable acute medical care facility. Each has 1,000-bed medical care unit. They are used for Armed forces and mercy mission to damaged locations, like after a [[Typhoon]].<ref>[http://www.nauticexpo.com/prod/general-dynamics-nassco/product-32138-195925.html Nuatic Exop, Oil tanker cargo ship, SAN CLEMENTE CLASS]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |title=Patient Care |website=Command Facilities |publisher=USNS Mercy |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323010700/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/Commandinfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |archivedate=23 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"med.navy.mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |title=Command Mission |website=USNS Mercy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813132035/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |archivedate=2009-08-13|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"med.navy.mil\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/logi-en/1997/lo-1610.htm |title=NATO Logistics Handbook: Chapter 16: Medical Support |work=nato.int |date=October 1997 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnscomfort/Pages/default.aspx|title=Home|work=navy.mil|accessdate=4 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426120150/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnscomfort/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate=26 April 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2012/02/16/usns-comforts-move-from-baltimore-to-norfolk-to-save-navy-time-money|title=USNS Comfort\u2019s Move From Baltimore To Norfolk To Save Navy Time & Money \u00ab CBS Baltimore|work=cbslocal.com|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\nEach ship is 894 feet long, with a beam of 105 feet and depths-draft of 64 feet. This is the maximum size, known as [[Panamax]], that can pass though the [[Panama Canal]]. All the ships in the class have a [[double hull]] bottom for safety. They came with anti-collision [[radar]], [[bacteria]]-[[enzyme]] [[sewage treatment]] plant and high-capacity clean [[ballast]] systems.\n<ref>Tanker Construction Program: Environmental Impact Statement, Volume 1, page 2-31</ref>\n<ref>[http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/large/nassco.htm shipbuildinghistory.com, NASSCO, San Diego CA]</ref>\n\n==Owners==\n*Aeron Marine Shipping Co.\n*Third Group, Inc.\n*Maritime Overseas Corp. (now [[