{"title_page": "Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon\n| image         = Vyloppilli.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b\n| pseudonym     = Vyloppilli\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1911|5|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Kaloor]], [[Kingdom of Cochin|Cochin]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1985|12|22|1911|5|11}}\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Poet\n| language      = [[Malayalam]]\n| nationality   = Indian\n| citizenship   = \n| period        = \n| genre         = Poetry\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = {{ublist|''Kudiyozhikkal''|''Kannikkoythu''|''Mambazham''|''Makarakoythu''|''Kaipavallari''|''Vida''}}\n| spouse        = Bhanumathi Amma\n| relatives     = Kochukuttan Kartha (father)<br>Nanikutty Amma (mother)\n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = {{ublist|1964&nbsp;[[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]]|1971&nbsp;[[Odakkuzhal Award]]|1971&nbsp;[[Sahitya Akademi Award]]|1981&nbsp;[[Vayalar Award]]}}\n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon''' (11 May 1911 \u2013 22 December 1985) (also written as '''Vailoppilli''') was an Indian poet of [[Malayalam literature]]. Known for his works such as ''Kudiyozhikkal'', ''Kannikkoythu'' and ''[[Mambazham (poem)|Mambazham]]'', Menon was the founder president of the [[Purogamana Kala Sahitya Sangham]], an organization of Kerala-based artists, writers and art and literature enthusiasts. He was a recipient of several honors including [[Sahitya Akademi Award]], [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry]], [[Vayalar Award]] and [[Odakkuzhal Award]].\n\n== Life and career ==\nVyloppilli Sreedhara Menon was born on May 11, 1911 in [[Kaloor]] in [[Kochi]] to Cheranellore Kochukuttan Kartha and Nanikutty Amma.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/Vailopillygraphy.htm |title=Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography |date=2019-01-28 |publisher=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |language=ml |access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref> Starting his early education was with a local ''Asan'' (teacher), Menon did his formal education initially at the Government Primary School, Kaloor and later at [[St. Albert's HSS, Ernakulam|St. Albert's High School, Ernakulam]] from where he completed the high school education in 1927. Subsequently, he graduated in Science from [[Maharaja's College, Ernakulam]]. He continued his education to pass BT degree from Seythapet Training College, Madras and started his career as a teacher in government service in 1931 at Kandassamkadavu Government High School.<ref name=\"Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralaculture.org/ |title=Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal |date=2019-01-28 |website=www.keralaculture.org |publisher=Department of Cultural Affairs, Government of Kerala |language=en |access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref> His teaching career took him to 20 different schools in Kerala until his retirement from service in 1966 as the head master of Ollur High School, the present day [[Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon Memorial Government Vocational Higher Secondary School]].<ref name=\"Govt.Vocational Higher Secondary School\">{{Cite web |url=http://thrissureducation.com/22059/index.htm |title=Govt.Vocational Higher Secondary School |date=2019-01-29 |website=thrissureducation.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He was involved with literary organizations such as [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi]] and Sahitya Pravartaka Sahakarana Sanghom; he was a member of the organizing committee of the former and the board of directors of the latter. He also served as the editor of the official magazine of the [[Kerala Sasthra Sahithya Parishad]].<ref name=\"Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal\" /> When [[Purogamana Kala Sahitya Sangham]], a forum of progressive writers led by leftist intellectuals and artists, was formed in 1981, he was selected as its founder president and he held the position until 1985.<ref name=\"EMS AS A LITERARY CRITIC AND CULTURAL ACTIVIST\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cpim.org/marxist/199801_marxist_ems_culture_pg.htm |title=EMS AS A LITERARY CRITIC AND CULTURAL ACTIVIST |last=P. Govinda Pillai |date=1998 |website=The Marxist |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\"History - \u0d2a\u0d41.\u0d15.\u0d38\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sites.google.com/site/purogamanakalasahithyasangham/assignments |title=History - \u0d2a\u0d41.\u0d15.\u0d38 |date=2019-01-29 |website=www.sites.google.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He represented Kerala thrice at the national poets' meetings of 1951 (Delhi), 1959 (Delhi) and 1965 (Bengaluru) and toured the [[Soviet Union]] in 1970.<ref name=\"\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.m3db.com/artists/6676 |title=\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon |date=2019-01-29 |website=www.m3db.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nMenon married Bhanumathi Amma, a school teacher, in 1955.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\" /> They had two sons, Sreekumar, an [[ayurvedic]] physician and Vijayakumar, a [[homeopathic]] doctor.<ref name=\"Report in Mathrubhumi\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.mathrubhumi.com/books/interview/vyloppilli-sreedhara-menon-1.2684642 |title=Report in Mathrubhumi |last=George Mathew Puthuppally |date=March 20, 2018 |website=Mathrubhumi |language=en |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> However, the couple had differences between themselves<ref name=\"Report in Manorama\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/literature/literaryworld/2018/06/28/vyloppilli-sreedhara-menon-wife-bhanumati-amma-kanneerpadam-poem.html |title=Report in Manorama |date=2019-01-29 |website=ManoramaOnline |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> and were staying separately when he died on December 22, 1985, succumbing to brain hemorrhage.<ref name=\"Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal\" /> Bhanumathi Amma survived him and died on June 26, 2018.<ref name=\"Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon\u2019s wife Thattattu Bhanumathi Amma passes away\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2018/jun/27/vyloppilli-sreedhara-menons-wife-thattattu-bhanumathi-amma-passes-away-1834194.html |title=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon's wife Thattattu Bhanumathi Amma passes away |date=June 27, 2018 |website=The New Indian Express |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Vyloppilli Ssamskrithi Bhavan, Thiruvananthapuram, Kerala, India.JPG|thumb|left|Vyloppilli Samskrithi Bhavan]]\nMenon started writing under the pen name ''Sree'' and his first poetry anthology, ''Kannikkoythu'' (The Maiden Harvest) was published in 1947; [[Kuttikrishna Marar]] opined that the poems signify a strong sprouting of Malayalam poetry that deviated from the romantic tradition prevalent during those times.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\" /> He is considered by literary historians as one of the major voices in Malayalam poetry who marked the transition from the [[romantic poetry|Romantic]] to the [[History of poetry#Modern developments|modern]] era.<ref name=\"Kurup2005\">{{cite book|author=O. N. V. Kurup|title=This Ancient Lyre: Selected Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6asUUvPUlTgC&pg=PR24|year=2005|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1791-1|pages=24\u2013}}</ref> A scientific insight into the historical roots of social evolution and a deeper understanding of the psychological undercurrents of the human mind characterise his poetry. His mastery of the medium is evident in all his poems both lyrical and narrative.<ref>''Kairaliyude Kadha'', N. Krishna Pillai, NBS, [[Kottayam]].</ref>\n\nMenon published around 20 books, composed of poems, plays and biographies.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\" /><ref name=\"Vyloppilli - list of works\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/VailoppilliBooks.htm |title=Vyloppilli - list of works |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Many critics consider the long poem ''Kudiyozhikkal'' (Eviction of the tenant) as his [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]].<ref name=\"Kudiyozhikkal on Good Reads\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/42812364-kudiyozhikkal |title=Kudiyozhikkal on Good Reads |date=2019-01-29 |website=www.goodreads.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> [[M. Leelavathy]] wrote that ''the poem is a ruthless self-examination of a middle class land owner who realizes that the future belongs not to himself but to his poor tenant whom he despises at heart''.<ref>''Malayala Kavitha Sahithya Charithram'', Dr. [[M. Leelavathy]], [[Kerala Sahithya Academy]], [[Thrissur]]</ref><ref>''Vyloppillikkavitha Sameeksha'', The State Institute of Languages, [[Trivandrum]]</ref> The poem has been translated into English by P. K. N. Panicker and is included in the book, ''Selected Poems of Valoppilli Sreedhara Menon''.{{ISBN|978-93-5207-076-3}} ''Vida'', ''Kannikkoythu'', ''Makarakoythu'' and ''Kaipavallari'' are among his other major works, all of which have won awards. ''Kanneerpadam'', a poem he wrote soon after his separation from his wife, is reported to be autobiographical.<ref name=\"Report in Mathrubhumi\" /><ref name=\"Report in Manorama\" /> ''Sahyante Makan'', a Malayalam film released in 1982, is based on a poem of the same name written by Menon.<ref name=\"\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon\" /><ref name=\"Sahyante Makan [1982]\">{{Cite web |url=https://malayalasangeetham.info/m.php?2755&cl=1 |title=Sahyante Makan [1982] |date=2019-01-29 |website=malayalasangeetham.info |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> One of his poems titled, ''Madathakkili'', was used as a song in the movie, [[Vajram (2004 film)|Vajrram]].<ref name=\"\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon\" />\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nVyloppilli Sreedhara Menon received the Soviet Land Nehru Award in 1964, the same year as the Kerala Sahitya Akademi awarded him their [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry|annual award for poetry]] fr his anthology, ''Kaipavallari''.<ref name=\"Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/ksa/Awards/poetry.htm |title=Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He received the [[Odakkuzhal Award]]  in 1971 for ''Vida''<ref>''Akhilavijnanakosam'', D.C. Books; Kottayam</ref> and the anthology was awarded the [[Sahitya Akademi Award|Kendra Sahithya Academy Award]], the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/awards.htm |title=Kendra Sahitya Academy Awards (Malayalam) |publisher=Public Relations Department, [[Government of Kerala]] |accessdate=11 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070524212356/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/awards.htm |archivedate=24 May 2007 }}</ref> His work, ''Makarakoythu'', was selected for the [[Vayalar Award]] in 1981.<ref name=\"Vayalar Award\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/ml_aw27.htm |title=Vayalar Award |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He was also a recipient of the Madras State Government Award, Kalyani Krishna Menon Prize and [[M. P. Paul]] Prize. An annual literary award, ''Vyloppilli Poetry Award'', has been instituted in his honour.<ref name=\"Vyloppilli Poetry Award 2018 - Vyloppilly Memorial Award Announced\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theindian.news/bineesh-puthuppanam-wins-vylopilly-poetry-award-2018-for-his-collection-of-poems-paalvili/ |title=Vyloppilli Poetry Award 2018 - Vyloppilly Memorial Award Announced |last=Menon |first=Jayashankar |date=2018-12-23 |website=The Indian.News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> The Department of Cultural Affairs of the [[Government of Kerala]] have built a multi-purpose cultural complex housing an open air auditorium,  art gallery and museum block in Nanthancode, [[Thiruvanathapuram]] and the complex has been named ''Vailoppilly Samskrithi Bhavan'' in honor of the poet.<ref name=\"Vailoppilly Samskrithi Bhavan\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralaculture.org/vyloppilli-samskriti-bhavan/285 |title=Vailoppilly Samskrithi Bhavan |date=2019-01-29 |website=Department of Cultural Affairs, Government of Kerala |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> The museum block also holds the personal belongings of Menon.<ref name=\"Vyloppilli Samskrithi Bhavan, Thiruvananthapuram\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.keralatourism.org/destination/vyloppilly-samskrithi-bhavan-thiruvananthapuram/113 |title=Vyloppilli Samskrithi Bhavan, Thiruvananthapuram |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Tourism |language=en |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Another institution that holds Menon's name is Government Vocational Higher Secondary School, Ollur, the institution where he served as the head master at the time of his retirement which is known as [[Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon Memorial Government Vocational Higher Secondary School]].<ref name=\"Govt.Vocational Higher Secondary School\" />\n\n== Works ==\n=== Poems ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=50em}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=106656 |title=Vailoppilli: sampoorna krithikal |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=2013 |publisher=Current books |isbn=9788122611335 |location=Thrissur}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Kudiyozhikkal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |year=1952 |isbn=9788122611168 |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Vyloppilliyude Balakavithakal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Mambazham |isbn=9788126422654}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Aprakasitha Rachanakal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=DC Books |isbn=9789386560582|year=2017 }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Anthi Chayunnu |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122606010}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Makarakoythu |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122606737}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Kaipavallari |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122606027}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Kanneerpadavum Mattu Pradhaana Kavithakalum |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=DC Books |isbn=9788126416332|year=2007 }}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=85349 |title=Kannikoythu |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=2006 |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122605471 |location=Thrissur |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=70712 |title=Vitthum kaikkottum: kavithakal |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |publisher=National Books |location=Kottayam}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=83810 |title=Charithrathile charu drishyam |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=1991 |publisher=Vailoppilly smaraka samithi |edition=2nd |location=Thrissur}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.maebag.com/Product/3265/Vida |title=Vida |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=DC Books |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.maebag.com/Product/19175/Kadalkaakkakal |title=Kadalkaakkakal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122609837 |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.maebag.com/Product/19166/Kunnimanikal |title=Kunnimanikal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=8122605117 |language=ml}}\n{{div col end}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''Sreerekha''\n*''Onappatukar''\n*''Kuruvikal''\n*''Minnaminni''\n*''Pachakkuthira''\n*''Mukulamala''\n*''Krishnamrigangal''\n*''Mambazham''\n*''Yugaparivarthanam''\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Plays ===\n*''Risyasringanum Alexandarum'' (Play)\n\n=== Short stories ===\n* Himavante Puthrikal\n\n=== Autobiography ===\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=81854 |title=Kavyaloka Smaranakal |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=1988}}\n\n=== Books and articles on Vyloppilli ===\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Vyloppilli-Sreedhara-Menon-Ronald-Russell/dp/B007QW9O7K |title=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |last=Ronald Cohn, Jesse Russell |publisher=VSD |year=2012 |language=en |asin=B007QW9O7K}}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Jayasree, V R |date=2013 |title=Imagery in the poetry of Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/handle/10603/7568 |publisher=Mahatma Gandhi University}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Vyloppilli Vakkukalude Manthrasakthi |last=M. K. Sanu |date=2011 |publisher=DC Books |isbn=9788126432110 |location=[Kottayam] |oclc=789150681}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://onlinestore.dcbooks.com/books/g-vyloppilly-edasseri#; |title=G, Vyloppilli, Edasseri |last=Osho, Osho |publisher=Keerthi Books}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://onlinestore.dcbooks.com/books/vyloppilli-patanangal#; |title=Vyloppilli Patanangal |last=Panmana Ramachandran Nair |first=Current Books |isbn=9788124020388}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/VailoppilliPage.htm |title=Portrait on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal |date=2019-01-28 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-28}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/VailoppilliBooks.htm |title=List of works |date=2019-01-28 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-28}}\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pX_AcS0u1_w |title=Mambazham-Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |last=Jyothibai Pariyadath |date=2011-10-20 |website=YouTube |access-date=2019-01-28}}\n\n{{commons category|Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon}}\n{{Sahitya Akademi Award For Malayalam}}\n{{Kerala Sahitya Akademi Fellowship}}\n{{Malayalam Literature |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menon, Vyloppilli Sreedhara}}\n[[Category:Malayalam poets]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sahitya Akademi Award in Malayalam]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]]\n[[Category:People from Ernakulam district]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon\n| image         = Vyloppilli.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b\n| pseudonym     = Vyloppilli\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1911|5|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Kaloor]], [[Kingdom of Cochin|Cochin]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1985|12|22|1911|5|11}}\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Poet\n| language      = [[Malayalam]]\n| nationality   = Indian\n| citizenship   = \n| period        = \n| genre         = Poetry\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = {{ublist|''Kudiyozhikkal''|''Kannikkoythu''|''Mambazham''|''Makarakoythu''|''Kaipavallari''|''Vida''}}\n| spouse        = Bhanumathi Amma\n| relatives     = Kochukuttan Kartha (father)<br>Nanikutty Amma (mother)\n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = {{ublist|1964&nbsp;[[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]]|1971&nbsp;[[Odakkuzhal Award]]|1971&nbsp;[[Sahitya Akademi Award]]|1981&nbsp;[[Vayalar Award]]}}\n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon''' (11 May 1911 \u2013 22 December 1985) (also written as '''Vailoppilli''') was an Indian poet of [[Malayalam literature]]. Known for his works such as ''Kudiyozhikkal'', ''Kannikkoythu'' and ''[[Mambazham (poem)|Mambazham]]'', Menon was the founder president of the [[Purogamana Kala Sahitya Sangham]], an organization of Kerala-based artists, writers and art and literature enthusiasts. He was a recipient of several honors including [[Sahitya Akademi Award]], [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry]], [[Vayalar Award]] and [[Odakkuzhal Award]].\n\n== Life and career ==\nVyloppilli Sreedhara Menon was born on May 11, 1911 in [[Kaloor]] in [[Kochi]] to Cheranellore Kochukuttan Kartha and Nanikutty Amma.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/Vailopillygraphy.htm |title=Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography |date=2019-01-28 |publisher=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |language=ml |access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref> Starting his early education was with a local ''Asan'' (teacher), Menon did his formal education initially at the Government Primary School, Kaloor and later at [[St. Albert's HSS, Ernakulam|St. Albert's High School, Ernakulam]] from where he completed the high school education in 1927. Subsequently, he graduated in Science from [[Maharaja's College, Ernakulam]]. He continued his education to pass BT degree from Seythapet Training College, Madras and started his career as a teacher in government service in 1931 at Kandassamkadavu Government High School.<ref name=\"Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralaculture.org/ |title=Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal |date=2019-01-28 |website=www.keralaculture.org |publisher=Department of Cultural Affairs, Government of Kerala |language=en |access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref> His teaching career took him to 20 different schools in Kerala until his retirement from service in 1966 as the head master of Ollur High School, the present day [[Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon Memorial Government Vocational Higher Secondary School]].<ref name=\"Govt.Vocational Higher Secondary School\">{{Cite web |url=http://thrissureducation.com/22059/index.htm |title=Govt.Vocational Higher Secondary School |date=2019-01-29 |website=thrissureducation.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He was involved with literary organizations such as [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi]] and Sahitya Pravartaka Sahakarana Sanghom; he was a member of the organizing committee of the former and the board of directors of the latter. He also served as the editor of the official magazine of the [[Kerala Sasthra Sahithya Parishad]].<ref name=\"Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal\" /> When [[Purogamana Kala Sahitya Sangham]], a forum of progressive writers led by leftist intellectuals and artists, was formed in 1981, he was selected as its founder president and he held the position until 1985.<ref name=\"EMS AS A LITERARY CRITIC AND CULTURAL ACTIVIST\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cpim.org/marxist/199801_marxist_ems_culture_pg.htm |title=EMS AS A LITERARY CRITIC AND CULTURAL ACTIVIST |last=P. Govinda Pillai |date=1998 |website=The Marxist |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\"History - \u0d2a\u0d41.\u0d15.\u0d38\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sites.google.com/site/purogamanakalasahithyasangham/assignments |title=History - \u0d2a\u0d41.\u0d15.\u0d38 |date=2019-01-29 |website=www.sites.google.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He represented Kerala thrice at the national poets' meetings of 1951 (Delhi), 1959 (Delhi) and 1965 (Bengaluru) and toured the [[Soviet Union]] in 1970.<ref name=\"\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.m3db.com/artists/6676 |title=\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon |date=2019-01-29 |website=www.m3db.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nMenon married Bhanumathi Amma, a school teacher, in 1955.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\" /> They had two sons, Sreekumar, an [[ayurvedic]] physician and Vijayakumar, a [[homeopathic]] doctor.<ref name=\"Report in Mathrubhumi\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.mathrubhumi.com/books/interview/vyloppilli-sreedhara-menon-1.2684642 |title=Report in Mathrubhumi |last=George Mathew Puthuppally |date=March 20, 2018 |website=Mathrubhumi |language=en |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> However, the couple had differences between themselves<ref name=\"Report in Manorama\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/literature/literaryworld/2018/06/28/vyloppilli-sreedhara-menon-wife-bhanumati-amma-kanneerpadam-poem.html |title=Report in Manorama |date=2019-01-29 |website=ManoramaOnline |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> and were staying separately when he died on December 22, 1985, succumbing to brain hemorrhage.<ref name=\"Vyloppilly Sreedhara Menon on Kerala Culture portal\" /> Bhanumathi Amma survived him and died on June 26, 2018.<ref name=\"Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon\u2019s wife Thattattu Bhanumathi Amma passes away\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2018/jun/27/vyloppilli-sreedhara-menons-wife-thattattu-bhanumathi-amma-passes-away-1834194.html |title=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon's wife Thattattu Bhanumathi Amma passes away |date=June 27, 2018 |website=The New Indian Express |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Vyloppilli Ssamskrithi Bhavan, Thiruvananthapuram, Kerala, India.JPG|thumb|left|Vyloppilli Samskrithi Bhavan]]\nMenon started writing under the pen name ''Sree'' and his first poetry anthology, ''Kannikkoythu'' (The Maiden Harvest) was published in 1947; [[Kuttikrishna Marar]] opined that the poems signify a strong sprouting of Malayalam poetry that deviated from the romantic tradition prevalent during those times.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\" /> He is considered by literary historians as one of the major voices in Malayalam poetry who marked the transition from the [[romantic poetry|Romantic]] to the [[History of poetry#Modern developments|modern]] era.<ref name=\"Kurup2005\">{{cite book|author=O. N. V. Kurup|title=This Ancient Lyre: Selected Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6asUUvPUlTgC&pg=PR24|year=2005|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1791-1|pages=24\u2013}}</ref> A scientific insight into the historical roots of social evolution and a deeper understanding of the psychological undercurrents of the human mind characterise his poetry. His mastery of the medium is evident in all his poems both lyrical and narrative.<ref>''Kairaliyude Kadha'', N. Krishna Pillai, NBS, [[Kottayam]].</ref>\n\nMenon published around 20 books, composed of poems, plays and biographies.<ref name=\"Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon - Biography\" /><ref name=\"Vyloppilli - list of works\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/VailoppilliBooks.htm |title=Vyloppilli - list of works |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Many critics consider the long poem ''Kudiyozhikkal'' (Eviction of the tenant) as his [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]].<ref name=\"Kudiyozhikkal on Good Reads\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/42812364-kudiyozhikkal |title=Kudiyozhikkal on Good Reads |date=2019-01-29 |website=www.goodreads.com |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> [[M. Leelavathy]] wrote that ''the poem is a ruthless self-examination of a middle class land owner who realizes that the future belongs not to himself but to his poor tenant whom he despises at heart''.<ref>''Malayala Kavitha Sahithya Charithram'', Dr. [[M. Leelavathy]], [[Kerala Sahithya Academy]], [[Thrissur]]</ref><ref>''Vyloppillikkavitha Sameeksha'', The State Institute of Languages, [[Trivandrum]]</ref> The poem has been translated into English by P. K. N. Panicker and is included in the book, ''Selected Poems of Valoppilli Sreedhara Menon''.{{ISBN|978-93-5207-076-3}} ''Vida'', ''Kannikkoythu'', ''Makarakoythu'' and ''Kaipavallari'' are among his other major works, all of which have won awards. ''Kanneerpadam'', a poem he wrote soon after his separation from his wife, is reported to be autobiographical.<ref name=\"Report in Mathrubhumi\" /><ref name=\"Report in Manorama\" /> ''Sahyante Makan'', a Malayalam film released in 1982, is based on a poem of the same name written by Menon.<ref name=\"\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon\" /><ref name=\"Sahyante Makan [1982]\">{{Cite web |url=https://malayalasangeetham.info/m.php?2755&cl=1 |title=Sahyante Makan [1982] |date=2019-01-29 |website=malayalasangeetham.info |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> One of his poems titled, ''Madathakkili'', was used as a song in the movie, [[Vajram (2004 film)|Vajrram]].<ref name=\"\u0d35\u0d48\u0d32\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d27\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d4b\u0d7b - Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon\" />\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nVyloppilli Sreedhara Menon received the Soviet Land Nehru Award in 1964, the same year as the Kerala Sahitya Akademi awarded him their [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry|annual award for poetry]] fr his anthology, ''Kaipavallari''.<ref name=\"Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/ksa/Awards/poetry.htm |title=Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award for Poetry |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He received the [[Odakkuzhal Award]]  in 1971 for ''Vida''<ref>''Akhilavijnanakosam'', D.C. Books; Kottayam</ref> and the anthology was awarded the [[Sahitya Akademi Award|Kendra Sahithya Academy Award]], the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/awards.htm |title=Kendra Sahitya Academy Awards (Malayalam) |publisher=Public Relations Department, [[Government of Kerala]] |accessdate=11 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070524212356/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/awards.htm |archivedate=24 May 2007 }}</ref> His work, ''Makarakoythu'', was selected for the [[Vayalar Award]] in 1981.<ref name=\"Vayalar Award\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/ml_aw27.htm |title=Vayalar Award |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> He was also a recipient of the Madras State Government Award, Kalyani Krishna Menon Prize and [[M. P. Paul]] Prize. An annual literary award, ''Vyloppilli Poetry Award'', has been instituted in his honour.<ref name=\"Vyloppilli Poetry Award 2018 - Vyloppilly Memorial Award Announced\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theindian.news/bineesh-puthuppanam-wins-vylopilly-poetry-award-2018-for-his-collection-of-poems-paalvili/ |title=Vyloppilli Poetry Award 2018 - Vyloppilly Memorial Award Announced |last=Menon |first=Jayashankar |date=2018-12-23 |website=The Indian.News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> The Department of Cultural Affairs of the [[Government of Kerala]] have built a multi-purpose cultural complex housing an open air auditorium,  art gallery and museum block in Nanthancode, [[Thiruvanathapuram]] and the complex has been named ''Vailoppilly Samskrithi Bhavan'' in honor of the poet.<ref name=\"Vailoppilly Samskrithi Bhavan\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralaculture.org/vyloppilli-samskriti-bhavan/285 |title=Vailoppilly Samskrithi Bhavan |date=2019-01-29 |website=Department of Cultural Affairs, Government of Kerala |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> The museum block also holds the personal belongings of Menon.<ref name=\"Vyloppilli Samskrithi Bhavan, Thiruvananthapuram\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.keralatourism.org/destination/vyloppilly-samskrithi-bhavan-thiruvananthapuram/113 |title=Vyloppilli Samskrithi Bhavan, Thiruvananthapuram |date=2019-01-29 |website=Kerala Tourism |language=en |access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Another institution that holds Menon's name is Government Vocational Higher Secondary School, Ollur, the institution where he served as the head master at the time of his retirement which is known as [[Vailoppilli Sreedhara Menon Memorial Government Vocational Higher Secondary School]].<ref name=\"Govt.Vocational Higher Secondary School\" />\n\n== Works ==\n=== Poems ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=50em}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=106656 |title=Vailoppilli: sampoorna krithikal |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=2013 |publisher=Current books |isbn=9788122611335 |location=Thrissur}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Kudiyozhikkal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |year=1952 |isbn=9788122611168 |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Vyloppilliyude Balakavithakal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Mambazham |isbn=9788126422654}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Aprakasitha Rachanakal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=DC Books |isbn=9789386560582|year=2017 }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Anthi Chayunnu |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122606010}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Makarakoythu |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122606737}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Kaipavallari |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122606027}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Kanneerpadavum Mattu Pradhaana Kavithakalum |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=DC Books |isbn=9788126416332|year=2007 }}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=85349 |title=Kannikoythu |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=2006 |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122605471 |location=Thrissur |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=70712 |title=Vitthum kaikkottum: kavithakal |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |publisher=National Books |location=Kottayam}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=83810 |title=Charithrathile charu drishyam |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=1991 |publisher=Vailoppilly smaraka samithi |edition=2nd |location=Thrissur}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.maebag.com/Product/3265/Vida |title=Vida |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=DC Books |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.maebag.com/Product/19175/Kadalkaakkakal |title=Kadalkaakkakal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=9788122609837 |language=ml}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.maebag.com/Product/19166/Kunnimanikal |title=Kunnimanikal |last=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |publisher=Current Books |isbn=8122605117 |language=ml}}\n{{div col end}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''Sreerekha''\n*''Onappatukar''\n*''Kuruvikal''\n*''Minnaminni''\n*''Pachakkuthira''\n*''Mukulamala''\n*''Krishnamrigangal''\n*''Mambazham''\n*''Yugaparivarthanam''\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Plays ===\n*''Risyasringanum Alexandarum'' (Play)\n\n=== Short stories ===\n* Himavante Puthrikal\n\n=== Autobiography ===\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=81854 |title=Kavyaloka Smaranakal |last=Sreedhara Menon |first=Vailoppilli |date=1988}}\n\n=== Books and articles on Vyloppilli ===\n* {{Cite book |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Vyloppilli-Sreedhara-Menon-Ronald-Russell/dp/B007QW9O7K |title=Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |last=Ronald Cohn, Jesse Russell |publisher=VSD |year=2012 |language=en |asin=B007QW9O7K}}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Jayasree, V R |date=2013 |title=Imagery in the poetry of Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/handle/10603/7568 |publisher=Mahatma Gandhi University}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Vyloppilli Vakkukalude Manthrasakthi |last=M. K. Sanu |date=2011 |publisher=DC Books |isbn=9788126432110 |location=[Kottayam] |oclc=789150681}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://onlinestore.dcbooks.com/books/g-vyloppilly-edasseri#; |title=G, Vyloppilli, Edasseri |last=Osho, Osho |publisher=Keerthi Books}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://onlinestore.dcbooks.com/books/vyloppilli-patanangal#; |title=Vyloppilli Patanangal |last=Panmana Ramachandran Nair |first=Current Books |isbn=9788124020388}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/VailoppilliPage.htm |title=Portrait on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal |date=2019-01-28 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-28}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Vailoppilli/Html/VailoppilliBooks.htm |title=List of works |date=2019-01-28 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-01-28}}\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pX_AcS0u1_w |title=Mambazham-Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon |last=Jyothibai Pariyadath |date=2011-10-20 |website=YouTube |access-date=2019-01-28}}\n\n{{commons category|Vyloppilli Sreedhara Menon}}\n{{Sahitya Akademi Award For Malayalam}}\n{{Kerala Sahitya Akademi Fellowship}}\n{{Malayalam Literature |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menon, Vyloppilli Sreedhara}}\n[[Category:Malayalam poets]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sahitya Akademi Award in Malayalam]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]]\n[[Category:People from Ernakulam district]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vyloppilli_Sreedhara_Menon"}
{"title_page": "Port, Templeport", "text_new": "[[File:Port, Templeport.jpg|thumb|Road beside Templeport Lough, County Cavan, Ireland, heading west.]]\n\n'''Port''' ({{Irish derived place name|Port meaning 'A Landing-Place'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nPort is bounded on the north by [[Muinaghan]] townland, on the west by [[Kildoagh]] and [[Corboy Glebe]] townlands, on the south by [[Ray, Templeport]] and [[Cloneary]] townlands and on the east by [[Cor, Templeport]] and [[Kilsallagh]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are Templeport Lough, Inch Island, woods, streams and spring wells. The 1836 Ordnance Survey Namebooks state-\n\n''The soil is light yellow clay intermixed with sand stone...The townland is bounded on the W. side by a large lake, on the E. bank of which is situated the parish church. It is a handsome modern building to which is attached a graveyard in which nearly all the Protestant inhabitants are buried. There is an island belonging to this townland near the centre of the lake.''\n\nPort is traversed by minor public roads and rural lanes.\n\nThe townland covers 335 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe old name of the townland was Templeport (now shortened to Port) which is the anglicisation of the Gaelic ''Teampall An Phoirt'' (\"The Church of the Port or Bank or Landing-Place\"). The church referred to is the old church on St. Mogue's Island in the middle of Port Lake. This church fell into disuse in medieval times and a new church was built on the opposite shore of the lake. It was forfeited to Queen Elizabeth in 1590 and started use as a Protestant church in about 1610. It is very unlikely that the island church ever served as the parish church because there was only one boat available and it would have been extremely inconvenient if not logistically impossible for hundreds of worshipers to go to and from the church in time for mass, especially in rough winter weather. It was built firstly for the convenience of any pilgrim wishing to go to St. Mogue's birthplace and secondly as an interment or mortuary chapel for the few family members attending burials on the island.\n\n==History==\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Aghavanme''.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf National Archives Dublin]</ref><ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref>\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the townland ''Aghowanny''.\n\nThe 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Port''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref>\n\n[[William Petty]]'s 1685 map depicts it as ''Port''.<ref>[http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#c=Cavan]</ref>\n\nAn 1809 map of ecclesiastical lands in Templeport depicts the townland as ''Templeport'' with a subdivision in the northeast part named ''Portlargy'' ({{Irish derived place name|Port L\u00e1irge meaning 'The Hillside of the Landing-Place'}})[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1809-tp-map.html]\n\nSaint [[M\u00e1ed\u00f3c of Ferns]], also known as St. Mogue, was born in the island of Breaghwee (Originally Inis Brechmaighe meaning the 'Island of  the \nWolf Plain', now called Inch Island which is an abbreviation and duplication of the Irish Inis) in Templeport Lake about 558 A.D.[http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/st-mogue-of-tp.html]\n\nThe earliest mention of the name in the annals of Ireland is in the Annals of the Four Masters for 1496 A.D.- ''M1496.17- Magauran, i.e. Donnell Bearnagh, Chief of Teallach-Eachdhach, was treacherously slain before the altar of the church of Teampall-an-phuirt, by Teige, the son of Hugh, son of Owen Magauran; and the marks of the blows aimed at him are still visible in the corners of the altar.''\n\nThe church had two different rights, one was ownership of the church lands (both termon lands and the site of the church and graveyard) and the other was ownership of the church tithes (also called the rectorial tithes or the rectory) which were a tenth of all the produce of the parish not owned by the church. These rights were often owned by different people and so had a different history, as set out below.\n\n'''Church Lands'''\n\nPort formed part of the termon or hospital lands belonging to Templeport Church and so its history belongs to the ecclesiastical history of the parish. It would have belonged to the parish priest and the erenach family rather than the McGovern chief. The earliest mention of the name in the Vatican archives is for  2 September 1414- ''To the archdeacon of Kilmore. Mandate to collate and assign to Magonius Macamragan, priest, of the diocese of Kilmore, if found fit, the perpetual vicarage, value not exceeding 6 marks, of Insula Brechungy alias Tempullapuret in the said diocese, collation and provision of which, on its voidance by the death of Andrew Macgamragan, was made to him by bishop Nicholas. He doubts whether the said collation and provision of the said vicarage which, as the pope has learned, is still void as above, holds good. Dignum [arbitramur]''.<ref>Calendar of Papal Registers Relating To Great Britain and Ireland, Volume 6, 1404-1415, ed. W H Bliss and J A Twemlow (London, 1904), p. 476.</ref> In the 16th century these ecclesiastical lands in Templeport were seized in the course of the [[Reformation in Ireland]] and kept first by the English monarch and then eventually granted to the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore]].\n\nAn Inquisition held in [[Cavan]] Town on 20 June 1588 valued the total vicarage of Templeport at \u00a310.\n\nAn Inquisition held in [[Cavan]] Town on 19 September 1590 found ''the termon or hospital lands of Templeport to consist of four polls of land at a yearly value of 4 shillings''. Port was one of these four polls.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/MonasticonHibernicumV1|page=[https://archive.org/details/MonasticonHibernicumV1/page/n90 71]|quote=Kilfert.|title=Monasticon Hibernicum: or, a history of the abbeys, priories, and other religious houses in Ireland; interspersed with memoirs of their several founders and benefactors, and of their abbots and other superiors, to the time of their final suppression|first=Mervyn|last=Archdall|date=14 September 1873|publisher=W. B. Kelly|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nBy grant dated 6 March 1605, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted a lease of ''the farm, termons or hospitals of Tampleporte containing 4 pulls for 21 years at an annual rent of 10 shillings'' to Sir [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]]. Port was one of these four pulls.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S6MUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA233&dq=cavan+Tampleporte&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiy8t3o-sjjAhVbiVwKHbjUAVIQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=cavan%20Tampleporte&f=false]</ref>\n\nBy grant dated 10 August 1607, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted a further lease of ''the farms, termons or hospitals of Templeport containing 2 pulls for 21 years at an annual rent of 13 shillings'' to the aforesaid Sir [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]] of [[Mellifont Abbey]], [[County Louth]]. This grant covered the two extra polls of ecclesiastical land in the parish which had been overlooked in the previous inquisitions and grants.\n\nA survey held by Sir [[John Davies (poet)]] at [[Cavan]] Town on 6 September 1608 stated that- ''the ecclesiastical lands of Templeporte were containing 6 pulls lying near the parish church and that the rectory was appropriated to the [[Abbey of Kells]], [[County Meath]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=popOAAAAIAAJ&dq=killfeart+templeporte+killadough&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=templeporte]</ref> Port was one of these six pulls.\n\nAn Inquisition held in [[Cavan]] Town on 25 September 1609 found ''the termon land of Templeport to consist of six polls of land, out of which the [[Bishop of Kilmore]] was entitled to a rent of 10 shillings and 2/3rd of a beef per annum''. Port was one of these six polls. The Inquisition then granted the lands to the Protestant Bishop of Kilmore.\n\nBy a deed dated 6 April 1612, Robert Draper, the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore and Ardagh]] granted a joint ''lease of 60 years over the termons or herenachs of, inter alia, 6 polls in Templepurt'' to [[Oliver Lambart, 1st Lord Lambart, Baron of Cavan]], of [[Kilbeggan]], [[County Westmeath]] and Sir [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]], of [[Mellifont Abbey]], [[County Louth]]. Port formed part of the six polls in this lease.\n\nBy deed dated 17 July 1639, [[William Bedell]], the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore]], extended the above lease of ''Templepart'' to Oliver Lambert\u2019s son, [[Charles Lambart, 1st Earl of Cavan]].\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor as ''The Lord of Cavan'', who also appears as proprietor of several other Templeport townlands in the same survey.\n\n'''Rectorial Tithes'''\n\nThe rectorial tithes were split between the local parish priest who received 1/3 and the Abbey of Kells who received 2/3, from medieval times until they were seized in the Dissolution of the Monasteries.\n\nA list of the rectories owned by King [[Henry VIII of England]] in 1542 included ''Templeporte''.<ref>[https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/399f6945-52dd-488f-b5ca-67b1ebee2197]</ref>\n\nIn 1587 [[Elizabeth I of England]] granted the rectory of ''Templeporte'' to Garret (otherwise Gerald) Fleming of Cabragh.\n\nOn 30 October 1603 the aforementioned Gerrald Fleming surrendered the rectory of ''Templeporte'' to King [[James VI and I]] and it was regranted to him for a term of 21 years.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NOpEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=Templeporte+-%22temple.+porte%22&source=bl&ots=XWUq-iU279&sig=ACfU3U0b7j0pzmsRAZHvk6kXEsnjPlr0zQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiokNW3qbbhAhXnUhUIHei8DegQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Templeporte%20-%22temple.%20porte%22&f=false]</ref> \n\nBy grant dated 22 December 1608, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted a lease of the rectories, churches, or chapels formerly belonging to Kells Abbey, including ''Templeporte'' to Gerald Fleminge of Cabragh, County Cavan.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA134&lpg=PA134&dq=%27%27Templeporte%27%27+Garret&source=bl&ots=sGV4wUjhEp&sig=ACfU3U0mP1uxoar0qOGb-BvYxf9wWd13qg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwih25KI2sjjAhUPWhUIHczeAjAQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=''Crodraghe''%20Garret&f=false]</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 1609 the aforementioned Gerrald Fleming sold the rectory of ''Templeporte'' to his son James Fleming and Walter Talbot of [[Ballyconnell]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PR111&lpg=PR111&dq=Templeporte+-%22temple.+porte%22&source=bl&ots=q1ovKk1-Vm&sig=ACfU3U33GHoNgmSL8I9RZRps4POAcS2nGg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihlav7qrbhAhV1SxUIHfDCD-04ChDoATAEegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=Templeporte%20-%22temple.%20porte%22&f=false]</ref> On 8 June 1619 the aforesaid James Fleming and Walter Talbot were pardoned by King [[James VI and I]] for obtaining the said rectory of ''Templeport'' without getting a licence from the king.\n\nAn Inquisition held at Cavan on 19 October 1616 stated that the aforementioned Gerald Fleming died on 5 April 1615 and his son Thomas Fleming (born 1589) succeeded to the rectorial tithes of ''Templeporte''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=RA6-PA9&dq=Clontegrigenie&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn2_as1PraAhVsLsAKHaGyBo0Q6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=crodragh&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1622 Thomas Moigne, the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore]] made a visitation to the parish. He found that the rectory was impropriate to the vicar of Templeport, John Patrick, who was not a resident, but that there was a curate resident. The annual value of the rectory was \u00a320. The church was in a ruinous condition and the parsonage was a timber house.\n\nOn 9 March 1669 King [[Charles II of England]] granted ''to Josias Hallington, incumbent of Templeport, Co. Cavan, the rectory of the said parish, forever''.\n\n'''18th century onwards'''\n\nMajor Edward Magauran was born in [[Ballymagovern]], County Cavan on 16 April 1746, the grandson of [[Colonel Bryan Magauran]], the Chief of the McGovern Clan who fought in the [[Battle of the Boyne]] for [[King James II]] against [[William III of England|William III]] of Orange. In his book ''Memoirs of Major M\u2019Gauran'', Volume I, Page 127 (London 1786), he states (about the year 1765)- ''Upon my return from Luxemburg, the General wrote to Mr. John M'Gauran, of '''Port''', in the County of Cavan, married to Ann O'Donnel, the General's cousin-german, telling him that a cousin of his, grand-son of Colonel Bryan M'Gauran, and son of Mary O'Donnel, was serving then in Loudon's regiment, quartered where he resided. Mr. M'Gauran, jealous of my prosperity, having many young sons of his own, whom he thought better entitled to the General's protection; but, notwithstanding, though he knew me to be his own near relation, wrote to the General, to inform him that I was not the son of Mary O'Donnel, but an impostor. The General shewed me the letter, and asked me the truth, which I told him, together with the motives I had for not revealing it sooner; all of which he approved, and matters seemed to be accommodated''.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memoirsofmajore_01mgau]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/memoirsofmajored02mgau]</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the name as ''Purt''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe 1809 map of ecclesiastical lands in Templeport depicts Port as still belonging to the Anglican Church of Ireland. The tenants on the land were- Robert Hume, Hugh Reilly, The widow of M. Kernan, John Lynch and James Hoey.[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1809-tp-map.html]\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list thirteen tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Purt&search=Search] ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Port Valuation Office Field books are available for 1839-1840.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00363.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00364.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00365.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=templeport&townland=port&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 108, being 47 males and 61 females. There were twenty houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 73, being 36 males and 37 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were thirteen houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n \n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists twenty four landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=191726&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EPort%3C/b%3E] - Port</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 74, being 40 males and 34 females. There were eleven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=109;size=200]</ref>\n\nIn 1871 the population of the townland was 52, being 29 males and 23 females. There were eleven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.(page 296 of census)<ref>[https://ia800200.us.archive.org/3/items/op1250167-1001/op1250167-1001.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1881 the population of the townland was 56, being 26 males and 30 females. There were eleven houses in the townland, one of which was uninhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1251357-1001#page/n297/mode/2up]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 the population of the townland was 49, being 23 males and 26 females. There were twelve houses in the townland, of which two were uninhabited.<ref>[http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/PageBrowser?path=Browse/Census%20(by%20geography)/Ireland/1891&active=yes&mno=442&tocstate=expandnew&display=sections&display=tables&display=pagetitles&pageseq=298&zoom=4]</ref>\n\nAccording to the story ''The Floating Stone of Inch Island'' (now found in the [[D\u00fachas]] School's Collection at jmhttp://www.duchas.ie/en/cbes/5082122/5037862) a cursing stone connected to the birth of Saint [[M\u00e1ed\u00f3c of Ferns]] or Mogue on Inch Island was buried in [[Ray, Templeport]] townland in the 1880s and is probably still there.\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are fourteen families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Bawnboy/Port//]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are only twelve families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Bawnboy/Port//]</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 1943 a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Bristol Beaufighter]] JL710 crash landed beside the island in Templeport Lough.[http://www.bawnboy.com/Beaufighter-JL710/index.html]\n\n==Church of Ireland clergy==\n\nThe list of Anglican rectors of Templeport is viewable at-[http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/clergy.htm].\n\n==Port School==\n\nThe Second Report from the Commissioners of Irish Education Inquiry dated 1826 stated that Terence McManus was the headmaster of the school which was a pay school with charges of 10d to 1/3d per annum. The schoolhouse was built of mud at a cost of 5 guineas. There were 77 pupils of which 71 were Roman Catholics and 6 were Church of Ireland. 46 were boys and 31 were girls. [http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/education-enquiry.html] It was closed before 1900.\n\n==Antiquities==\n\n# St. Mogue's ruined church on St. Mogue's Island, built about 1500 to replace an earlier church.<ref name=\"Cavan' 1940 pp. 154-156\">''Ecclesiastical Remains in Co. Cavan'' by T. G. F. Paterson and O. Davies in Ulster Journal of Archaeology, Third Series, Vol. 3 (1940), pp. 154-156</ref><ref name=\"County Cavan' 1948 pp. 73-118\">''The Churches of County Cavan'' by O. Davies in The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Vol. 78, No. 2 (Dec., 1948), pp. 73-118.</ref><ref>Site number 1692 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated on a natural island in Templeport Lough. Davies (1948, 116) noted documentary evidence for a church here in 1496. Patterson and Davies (1940, 154-6) described foundations of a rectangular drystone-built church (int. dims. 12m ENE-WSW; 5.3m NNW-SSE). They recorded that E wall then stood to a height of 0.9m and that S wall had been destroyed at W corner and another wall of rough ashlar standing about 6m high had been built across it. The W wall according to their observations contains a large rectangular window which they suggested was 'a type unusual in ecclesiastical buildings, in this position'. Within the graveyard they found several querns and architectural fragments indicative of the late 15th or early 16th century. Not visited. (CUCAP BGQ 69)''.</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/templeport-burials.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/stmogues-island-burial-register.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/headstone-inscriptions-st-mogues-island.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/st-mogues-island/draft-stmogues-conservation-plan.pdf]</ref>\n# Templeport Protestant Church erected 1815 to replace an earlier church built about 1400.[http://www.buildingsofireland.ie/niah/search.jsp?type=record&county=CV&regno=40401303] <ref name=\"Cavan' 1940 pp. 154-156\"/><ref name=\"County Cavan' 1948 pp. 73-118\"/><ref>Site number 1693 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995</ref> <ref>[http://www.igp-web.com/IGPArchives/ire/cavan/photos/tombstones/cavan-templeport/index.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/headstones.htm]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/memorialindex.htm]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/burials-stpeters/index.php]</ref>\n# Templeport House <ref>[http://www.buildingsofireland.ie/niah/search.jsp?type=record&county=CV&regno=40400914]</ref>\n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 1050 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is referred to as-\n''Raised oval area (int. dims. c. 43m ENE-WSW; c. 32m NNW-SSE) enclosed by a substantial earthen bank and a wide, deep fosse. Break in bank at S with accompanying causeway represents original entrance''.</ref> \n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 1051 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is referred to as-\n''Raised circular area (int. diam. 20.2m) enclosed by a low earthen bank and the remains of a fosse which has been deepened and incorporated into the field boundary from E-SE-S. Narrow break in bank at NW may represent original entrance''.</ref> \n# A crann\u00f3g 170 metres from the shore in Templeport Lough.<ref>Site number 1587 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is referred to as- ''Small circular island (diam. c. 17m) marked on all OS eds., c. 25m N of St Mogue's island on which is situated an early ecclesiastical site (CV013-049----), and 170m from the shoreline. Davies (1948, 116) described it as probably being a crann\u00f3g. (CUCAP BGQ 69)''.</ref> \n# A sandstone Beehive [[Quern-stone]][http://www.templeport.ie/magh-slecht-dara-fort/plain-of-blood.pdf] <ref>Ulster Journal of Archaeology, Vol. 59 (2000), p.88.</ref>\n# A Foot Bridge over the stream\n\n==See also==\n* [[Domhnall \u2018Bernach\u2019 M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Port, Templeport.jpg|thumb|Road beside Templeport Lough, County Cavan, Ireland, heading west.]]\n\n'''Port''' ({{Irish derived place name|Port meaning 'A Landing-Place'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nPort is bounded on the north by [[Muinaghan]] townland, on the west by [[Kildoagh]] and [[Corboy Glebe]] townlands, on the south by [[Ray, Templeport]] and [[Cloneary]] townlands and on the east by [[Cor, Templeport]] and [[Kilsallagh]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are Templeport Lough, Inch Island, woods, streams and spring wells. The 1836 Ordnance Survey Namebooks state-\n\n''The soil is light yellow clay intermixed with sand stone...The townland is bounded on the W. side by a large lake, on the E. bank of which is situated the parish church. It is a handsome modern building to which is attached a graveyard in which nearly all the Protestant inhabitants are buried. There is an island belonging to this townland near the centre of the lake.''\n\nPort is traversed by minor public roads and rural lanes.\n\nThe townland covers 335 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe old name of the townland was Templeport (now shortened to Port) which is the anglicisation of the Gaelic ''Teampall An Phoirt'' (\"The Church of the Port or Bank or Landing-Place\"). The church referred to is the old church on St. Mogue's Island in the middle of Port Lake. This church fell into disuse in medieval times and a new church was built on the opposite shore of the lake. It was forfeited to Queen Elizabeth in 1590 and started use as a Protestant church in about 1610. It is very unlikely that the island church ever served as the parish church because there was only one boat available and it would have been extremely inconvenient if not logistically impossible for hundreds of worshipers to go to and from the church in time for mass, especially in rough winter weather. It was built firstly for the convenience of any pilgrim wishing to go to St. Mogue's birthplace and secondly as an interment or mortuary chapel for the few family members attending burials on the island.\n\n==History==\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Aghavanme''.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf National Archives Dublin]</ref><ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref>\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the townland ''Aghowanny''.\n\nThe 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Port''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref>\n\nAn 1809 map of ecclesiastical lands in Templeport depicts the townland as ''Templeport'' with a subdivision in the northeast part named ''Portlargy'' ({{Irish derived place name|Port L\u00e1irge meaning 'The Hillside of the Landing-Place'}})[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1809-tp-map.html]\n\nSaint [[M\u00e1ed\u00f3c of Ferns]], also known as St. Mogue, was born in the island of Breaghwee (Originally Inis Brechmaighe meaning the 'Island of  the \nWolf Plain', now called Inch Island which is an abbreviation and duplication of the Irish Inis) in Templeport Lake about 558 A.D.[http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/st-mogue-of-tp.html]\n\nThe earliest mention of the name in the annals of Ireland is in the Annals of the Four Masters for 1496 A.D.- ''M1496.17- Magauran, i.e. Donnell Bearnagh, Chief of Teallach-Eachdhach, was treacherously slain before the altar of the church of Teampall-an-phuirt, by Teige, the son of Hugh, son of Owen Magauran; and the marks of the blows aimed at him are still visible in the corners of the altar.''\n\nThe church had two different rights, one was ownership of the church lands (both termon lands and the site of the church and graveyard) and the other was ownership of the church tithes (also called the rectorial tithes or the rectory) which were a tenth of all the produce of the parish not owned by the church. These rights were often owned by different people and so had a different history, as set out below.\n\n'''Church Lands'''\n\nPort formed part of the termon or hospital lands belonging to Templeport Church and so its history belongs to the ecclesiastical history of the parish. It would have belonged to the parish priest and the erenach family rather than the McGovern chief. The earliest mention of the name in the Vatican archives is for  2 September 1414- ''To the archdeacon of Kilmore. Mandate to collate and assign to Magonius Macamragan, priest, of the diocese of Kilmore, if found fit, the perpetual vicarage, value not exceeding 6 marks, of Insula Brechungy alias Tempullapuret in the said diocese, collation and provision of which, on its voidance by the death of Andrew Macgamragan, was made to him by bishop Nicholas. He doubts whether the said collation and provision of the said vicarage which, as the pope has learned, is still void as above, holds good. Dignum [arbitramur]''.<ref>Calendar of Papal Registers Relating To Great Britain and Ireland, Volume 6, 1404-1415, ed. W H Bliss and J A Twemlow (London, 1904), p. 476.</ref> In the 16th century these ecclesiastical lands in Templeport were seized in the course of the [[Reformation in Ireland]] and kept first by the English monarch and then eventually granted to the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore]].\n\nAn Inquisition held in [[Cavan]] Town on 20 June 1588 valued the total vicarage of Templeport at \u00a310.\n\nAn Inquisition held in [[Cavan]] Town on 19 September 1590 found ''the termon or hospital lands of Templeport to consist of four polls of land at a yearly value of 4 shillings''. Port was one of these four polls.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/MonasticonHibernicumV1|page=[https://archive.org/details/MonasticonHibernicumV1/page/n90 71]|quote=Kilfert.|title=Monasticon Hibernicum: or, a history of the abbeys, priories, and other religious houses in Ireland; interspersed with memoirs of their several founders and benefactors, and of their abbots and other superiors, to the time of their final suppression|first=Mervyn|last=Archdall|date=14 September 1873|publisher=W. B. Kelly|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nBy grant dated 6 March 1605, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted a lease of ''the farm, termons or hospitals of Tampleporte containing 4 pulls for 21 years at an annual rent of 10 shillings'' to Sir [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]]. Port was one of these four pulls.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S6MUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA233&dq=cavan+Tampleporte&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiy8t3o-sjjAhVbiVwKHbjUAVIQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=cavan%20Tampleporte&f=false]</ref>\n\nBy grant dated 10 August 1607, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted a further lease of ''the farms, termons or hospitals of Templeport containing 2 pulls for 21 years at an annual rent of 13 shillings'' to the aforesaid Sir [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]] of [[Mellifont Abbey]], [[County Louth]]. This grant covered the two extra polls of ecclesiastical land in the parish which had been overlooked in the previous inquisitions and grants.\n\nA survey held by Sir [[John Davies (poet)]] at [[Cavan]] Town on 6 September 1608 stated that- ''the ecclesiastical lands of Templeporte were containing 6 pulls lying near the parish church and that the rectory was appropriated to the [[Abbey of Kells]], [[County Meath]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=popOAAAAIAAJ&dq=killfeart+templeporte+killadough&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=templeporte]</ref> Port was one of these six pulls.\n\nAn Inquisition held in [[Cavan]] Town on 25 September 1609 found ''the termon land of Templeport to consist of six polls of land, out of which the [[Bishop of Kilmore]] was entitled to a rent of 10 shillings and 2/3rd of a beef per annum''. Port was one of these six polls. The Inquisition then granted the lands to the Protestant Bishop of Kilmore.\n\nBy a deed dated 6 April 1612, Robert Draper, the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore and Ardagh]] granted a joint ''lease of 60 years over the termons or herenachs of, inter alia, 6 polls in Templepurt'' to [[Oliver Lambart, 1st Lord Lambart, Baron of Cavan]], of [[Kilbeggan]], [[County Westmeath]] and Sir [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]], of [[Mellifont Abbey]], [[County Louth]]. Port formed part of the six polls in this lease.\n\nBy deed dated 17 July 1639, [[William Bedell]], the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore]], extended the above lease of ''Templepart'' to Oliver Lambert\u2019s son, [[Charles Lambart, 1st Earl of Cavan]].\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor as ''The Lord of Cavan'', who also appears as proprietor of several other Templeport townlands in the same survey.\n\n'''Rectorial Tithes'''\n\nThe rectorial tithes were split between the local parish priest who received 1/3 and the Abbey of Kells who received 2/3, from medieval times until they were seized in the Dissolution of the Monasteries.\n\nA list of the rectories owned by King [[Henry VIII of England]] in 1542 included ''Templeporte''.<ref>[https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/399f6945-52dd-488f-b5ca-67b1ebee2197]</ref>\n\nIn 1587 [[Elizabeth I of England]] granted the rectory of ''Templeporte'' to Garret (otherwise Gerald) Fleming of Cabragh.\n\nOn 30 October 1603 the aforementioned Gerrald Fleming surrendered the rectory of ''Templeporte'' to King [[James VI and I]] and it was regranted to him for a term of 21 years.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NOpEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=Templeporte+-%22temple.+porte%22&source=bl&ots=XWUq-iU279&sig=ACfU3U0b7j0pzmsRAZHvk6kXEsnjPlr0zQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiokNW3qbbhAhXnUhUIHei8DegQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Templeporte%20-%22temple.%20porte%22&f=false]</ref> \n\nBy grant dated 22 December 1608, along with other lands, King [[James VI and I]] granted a lease of the rectories, churches, or chapels formerly belonging to Kells Abbey, including ''Templeporte'' to Gerald Fleminge of Cabragh, County Cavan.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA134&lpg=PA134&dq=%27%27Templeporte%27%27+Garret&source=bl&ots=sGV4wUjhEp&sig=ACfU3U0mP1uxoar0qOGb-BvYxf9wWd13qg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwih25KI2sjjAhUPWhUIHczeAjAQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=''Crodraghe''%20Garret&f=false]</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 1609 the aforementioned Gerrald Fleming sold the rectory of ''Templeporte'' to his son James Fleming and Walter Talbot of [[Ballyconnell]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PR111&lpg=PR111&dq=Templeporte+-%22temple.+porte%22&source=bl&ots=q1ovKk1-Vm&sig=ACfU3U33GHoNgmSL8I9RZRps4POAcS2nGg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihlav7qrbhAhV1SxUIHfDCD-04ChDoATAEegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=Templeporte%20-%22temple.%20porte%22&f=false]</ref> On 8 June 1619 the aforesaid James Fleming and Walter Talbot were pardoned by King [[James VI and I]] for obtaining the said rectory of ''Templeport'' without getting a licence from the king.\n\nAn Inquisition held at Cavan on 19 October 1616 stated that the aforementioned Gerald Fleming died on 5 April 1615 and his son Thomas Fleming (born 1589) succeeded to the rectorial tithes of ''Templeporte''.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=RA6-PA9&dq=Clontegrigenie&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn2_as1PraAhVsLsAKHaGyBo0Q6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=crodragh&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1622 Thomas Moigne, the Anglican [[Bishop of Kilmore]] made a visitation to the parish. He found that the rectory was impropriate to the vicar of Templeport, John Patrick, who was not a resident, but that there was a curate resident. The annual value of the rectory was \u00a320. The church was in a ruinous condition and the parsonage was a timber house.\n\nOn 9 March 1669 King [[Charles II of England]] granted ''to Josias Hallington, incumbent of Templeport, Co. Cavan, the rectory of the said parish, forever''.\n\n'''18th century onwards'''\n\nMajor Edward Magauran was born in [[Ballymagovern]], County Cavan on 16 April 1746, the grandson of [[Colonel Bryan Magauran]], the Chief of the McGovern Clan who fought in the [[Battle of the Boyne]] for [[King James II]] against [[William III of England|William III]] of Orange. In his book ''Memoirs of Major M\u2019Gauran'', Volume I, Page 127 (London 1786), he states (about the year 1765)- ''Upon my return from Luxemburg, the General wrote to Mr. John M'Gauran, of '''Port''', in the County of Cavan, married to Ann O'Donnel, the General's cousin-german, telling him that a cousin of his, grand-son of Colonel Bryan M'Gauran, and son of Mary O'Donnel, was serving then in Loudon's regiment, quartered where he resided. Mr. M'Gauran, jealous of my prosperity, having many young sons of his own, whom he thought better entitled to the General's protection; but, notwithstanding, though he knew me to be his own near relation, wrote to the General, to inform him that I was not the son of Mary O'Donnel, but an impostor. The General shewed me the letter, and asked me the truth, which I told him, together with the motives I had for not revealing it sooner; all of which he approved, and matters seemed to be accommodated''.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memoirsofmajore_01mgau]</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/memoirsofmajored02mgau]</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the name as ''Purt''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe 1809 map of ecclesiastical lands in Templeport depicts Port as still belonging to the Anglican Church of Ireland. The tenants on the land were- Robert Hume, Hugh Reilly, The widow of M. Kernan, John Lynch and James Hoey.[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1809-tp-map.html]\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list thirteen tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Purt&search=Search] ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Port Valuation Office Field books are available for 1839-1840.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00363.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00364.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00365.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/search/vob/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&year_from=&year_to=&dd_dd=&dd_mm=&dd_yyyy=&book=&county=cavan&barony=&parish=templeport&townland=port&last_name_other_or_lessor=&first_name_other_or_lessor=&search=Search]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 108, being 47 males and 61 females. There were twenty houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 73, being 36 males and 37 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were thirteen houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n \n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists twenty four landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=191726&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EPort%3C/b%3E] - Port</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 74, being 40 males and 34 females. There were eleven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=109;size=200]</ref>\n\nIn 1871 the population of the townland was 52, being 29 males and 23 females. There were eleven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.(page 296 of census)<ref>[https://ia800200.us.archive.org/3/items/op1250167-1001/op1250167-1001.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1881 the population of the townland was 56, being 26 males and 30 females. There were eleven houses in the townland, one of which was uninhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1251357-1001#page/n297/mode/2up]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 the population of the townland was 49, being 23 males and 26 females. There were twelve houses in the townland, of which two were uninhabited.<ref>[http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/PageBrowser?path=Browse/Census%20(by%20geography)/Ireland/1891&active=yes&mno=442&tocstate=expandnew&display=sections&display=tables&display=pagetitles&pageseq=298&zoom=4]</ref>\n\nAccording to the story ''The Floating Stone of Inch Island'' (now found in the [[D\u00fachas]] School's Collection at jmhttp://www.duchas.ie/en/cbes/5082122/5037862) a cursing stone connected to the birth of Saint [[M\u00e1ed\u00f3c of Ferns]] or Mogue on Inch Island was buried in [[Ray, Templeport]] townland in the 1880s and is probably still there.\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are fourteen families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Bawnboy/Port//]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are only twelve families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Bawnboy/Port//]</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 1943 a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Bristol Beaufighter]] JL710 crash landed beside the island in Templeport Lough.[http://www.bawnboy.com/Beaufighter-JL710/index.html]\n\n==Church of Ireland clergy==\n\nThe list of Anglican rectors of Templeport is viewable at-[http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/clergy.htm].\n\n==Port School==\n\nThe Second Report from the Commissioners of Irish Education Inquiry dated 1826 stated that Terence McManus was the headmaster of the school which was a pay school with charges of 10d to 1/3d per annum. The schoolhouse was built of mud at a cost of 5 guineas. There were 77 pupils of which 71 were Roman Catholics and 6 were Church of Ireland. 46 were boys and 31 were girls. [http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/education-enquiry.html] It was closed before 1900.\n\n==Antiquities==\n\n# St. Mogue's ruined church on St. Mogue's Island, built about 1500 to replace an earlier church.<ref name=\"Cavan' 1940 pp. 154-156\">''Ecclesiastical Remains in Co. Cavan'' by T. G. F. Paterson and O. Davies in Ulster Journal of Archaeology, Third Series, Vol. 3 (1940), pp. 154-156</ref><ref name=\"County Cavan' 1948 pp. 73-118\">''The Churches of County Cavan'' by O. Davies in The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Vol. 78, No. 2 (Dec., 1948), pp. 73-118.</ref><ref>Site number 1692 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated on a natural island in Templeport Lough. Davies (1948, 116) noted documentary evidence for a church here in 1496. Patterson and Davies (1940, 154-6) described foundations of a rectangular drystone-built church (int. dims. 12m ENE-WSW; 5.3m NNW-SSE). They recorded that E wall then stood to a height of 0.9m and that S wall had been destroyed at W corner and another wall of rough ashlar standing about 6m high had been built across it. The W wall according to their observations contains a large rectangular window which they suggested was 'a type unusual in ecclesiastical buildings, in this position'. Within the graveyard they found several querns and architectural fragments indicative of the late 15th or early 16th century. Not visited. (CUCAP BGQ 69)''.</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/templeport-burials.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/stmogues-island-burial-register.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/headstone-inscriptions-st-mogues-island.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/st-mogues-island/draft-stmogues-conservation-plan.pdf]</ref>\n# Templeport Protestant Church erected 1815 to replace an earlier church built about 1400.[http://www.buildingsofireland.ie/niah/search.jsp?type=record&county=CV&regno=40401303] <ref name=\"Cavan' 1940 pp. 154-156\"/><ref name=\"County Cavan' 1948 pp. 73-118\"/><ref>Site number 1693 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995</ref> <ref>[http://www.igp-web.com/IGPArchives/ire/cavan/photos/tombstones/cavan-templeport/index.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/headstones.htm]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/stpeters-church/memorialindex.htm]</ref><ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/burials-stpeters/index.php]</ref>\n# Templeport House <ref>[http://www.buildingsofireland.ie/niah/search.jsp?type=record&county=CV&regno=40400914]</ref>\n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 1050 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is referred to as-\n''Raised oval area (int. dims. c. 43m ENE-WSW; c. 32m NNW-SSE) enclosed by a substantial earthen bank and a wide, deep fosse. Break in bank at S with accompanying causeway represents original entrance''.</ref> \n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 1051 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is referred to as-\n''Raised circular area (int. diam. 20.2m) enclosed by a low earthen bank and the remains of a fosse which has been deepened and incorporated into the field boundary from E-SE-S. Narrow break in bank at NW may represent original entrance''.</ref> \n# A crann\u00f3g 170 metres from the shore in Templeport Lough.<ref>Site number 1587 in \u201cArchaeological Inventory of County Cavan\u201d, Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is referred to as- ''Small circular island (diam. c. 17m) marked on all OS eds., c. 25m N of St Mogue's island on which is situated an early ecclesiastical site (CV013-049----), and 170m from the shoreline. Davies (1948, 116) described it as probably being a crann\u00f3g. (CUCAP BGQ 69)''.</ref> \n# A sandstone Beehive [[Quern-stone]][http://www.templeport.ie/magh-slecht-dara-fort/plain-of-blood.pdf] <ref>Ulster Journal of Archaeology, Vol. 59 (2000), p.88.</ref>\n# A Foot Bridge over the stream\n\n==See also==\n* [[Domhnall \u2018Bernach\u2019 M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port,_Templeport"}
